The paper focuses on investigating the performance of LTE Multicast-Broadcast Single-Frequency Networks (MBSFN) for vehicular communications, which falls under the category of networked systems and communication in computer science. Therefore, cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of Multimedia Broadcast/Multicast Service (MBMS) for point-to-multipoint transmission, which relates to multimedia systems and human-computer interaction, making cs.MM (Multimedia) a likely sub-category as well. The analysis of latency and resource utilization involves the use of information theory and communication theory, which falls under cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper also discusses the prediction of system behavior, which relates to system and control theory, making cs.SY (Systems and Control) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the overhead caused by vehicular traffic, which relates to security and privacy, making cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) a possible sub-category.
